<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-06-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-06-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="208" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d208">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 339.112C42/6.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-06-14"><hi rend="italic">June 14,
                                1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 52.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to previous correspondence on
                            the subject, I inclose for your information and guidance a copy of a
                            letter from the Secretary of the Navy<note n="1" xml:id="d208fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> in which he states that his Department concurs in
                            the opinion of this Department that the incident growing out of the rude
                            behavior of the guard of the barracks in the city of Santo Domingo to
                            the commanding officer of the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Chester</hi>
                            may now be considered as closed.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>